         <abstract>
            <p>Conventionally, the uneven impact of inflation is recognized for flows, but not for the discount rate relevant for the capital expenditure decision. Because this impact on the discount rate cannot be a priori assumed uniform across firms or projects, a need exists to recognize these disproportionate effects on discount rates to arrive at sound decisions. Their recognition, however, complicates the commonly prescribed capital expenditure decision procedures whether in either nominal or real terms. This paper describes conceptual sources leading to the uneven impact of inflation and suggests a proper way to reflect this on the discount rate within the capital asset pricing model framework. Consequent implications for operational aspects of budgeting procedures are examined.</p>
         </abstract>
